Brigadier General '''Lumley O W Jones''' (1887–1918) was the last [[United Kingdom|British]] [[General officer]] to die in the [[First World War]].
Born in 1887 at [[Llandyssil]] in [[Wales]], Jones was the son of Richard and Catherine Jones of [[Cefn Bryntalch]]. He had started the First World War as a [[Captain (armed forces)|captain]] in the [[Essex Regiment#First World War (1914-1918)|2nd Essex Regiment]] and took part in nearly every battle on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. By 1918 he reached the rank of [[brigadier general]] and was commander of the [[13th Infantry Brigade]]. He was also made a [[Chevalier of the Legion of Honour]] ([[France]]).
Jones died of [[pneumonia]] on 14 September 1918 aged 41 and was buried at the [[Bagneux British Cemetery]] at [[Gezaincourt]]. He was the last of 12 British General Officers to die on [[the Somme]].<ref>http://www. twgpp.org/information.php?id=2776855, with photograph of headstone</ref><ref>http://www.ww1wargraves.co.uk/ww1_cemeteries/ww1_cemetery_b.asp</ref> A photo of his head stone can be seen [http://www.ww1wargraves.co.uk/ww1_cemeteries/ww1_cemetery_b.asp here].
